# scripts/test/ui/ij-preservation.t47
#
# UI regression test: the keyboard and softmenu layer, and the promise that the
# matrix editor and the vector functions leave the user's I and J alone
# (upstream MR !1553).
#
# Runs under the GTK front end, NOT under t47:
#
#   xvfb-run -a ./c47 --reset --script <this file>
#
# press is the only DSL command that needs GTK, and --headless is GTK-less by
# design, so a keyboard test has to use c47 (or r47) without --headless. The
# lane script scripts/test/run-ui.sh does exactly that; this file is the thing
# it runs.
#
# Exit 0 = every check passed. Exit 1 = the named check failed, and c47 returns
# the script's status (c47-gtk.c:540-549), which is what the lane gates on.

proc check {what got want} {
  if {$got ne $want} {
    error "FAIL $what: got '$got' want '$want'"
  }
  puts "ok   $what"
}

# --- the keyboard reaches the calculator at all ------------------------------
# Guard check: if press stops working, everything below is vacuous.
nim 0.35
press "@k 02"
check "press @k 02 (sqrt) of 0.35" [reg X] 0.5916079783099616042567328291561617

# The keyval forms are what c47 has and t47 does not; assert one so this file
# fails loudly if it is ever run through the headless front end by mistake.
nim 2
press ENTER
nim 4
press "/"
check "press ENTER and '/' (GTK-decoded forms) give 2/4" [reg X] 0.5

# --- softmenu decode ---------------------------------------------------------
# F1..F6 go through btnFnClicked, which item and xeq cannot reach.
menu EXP
nim 0.35
press F1
check "menu EXP, F1 (x^3) of 0.35" [reg X] 0.042875

# --- MR !1553: the matrix editor must not spend the user's I and J -----------
# Sentinels are deliberately not 0/1: the editor's own cursor starts there, so
# a clobber that happened to write the same value would not show.
nim 5
sto I
nim 6
sto J
check "I set before the edit" [reg I] 5
check "J set before the edit" [reg J] 6

# 1526 M.DIM (3x3), 51 RCL, 1529 M.EDIT; in M_EDIT F5/F6 are left/right and
# f-shifted are up/down. This is the navigation that only keys can drive.
nim 3
nim 3
item 1526 00
item 51 00
item 1529
press F6
press @f
press F6
check "I survives matrix-editor navigation" [reg I] 5
check "J survives matrix-editor navigation" [reg J] 6

# --- MR !1553: the vector functions must not spend them either ---------------
# 2485 STOVEL1, 2482 RCLVEL1, 36 x<>y. These are not in the testSuite dispatch
# table, which is why the corpus cannot cover them and this file has to.
#
# The operand placement is not optional and getting it wrong makes every check
# below vacuous. fnStoreVElement wants the matrix in Y and the value in X
# (store.c:580); fnRecallVElement wants it in X (recall.c:440). Feed either the
# wrong stack and it prints "is not a matrix", returns without ever touching
# I/J, and the assertions pass while testing nothing. The round-trip check
# below exists to prove the functions really ran.
#
# M.EDIT leaves the matrix in X, so recall it fresh rather than relying on what
# the editor left behind.
item 51 00
nim 0.35
item 2485
check "I survives STOVEL1" [reg I] 5
check "J survives STOVEL1" [reg J] 6

# STOVEL leaves X=value, Y=matrix, so swap before recalling.
item 36
item 2482
check "I survives RCLVEL1" [reg I] 5
check "J survives RCLVEL1" [reg J] 6

# Positive control for the two checks above: element 1 reads back what STOVEL1
# put there. If either function had bailed on a bad operand, this is 0 or the
# matrix itself, and the I/J checks above were measuring nothing.
check "STOVEL1/RCLVEL1 round-trip - proves both actually ran" [reg X] 0.35

# The reported failure mode was a drift of one per call, which a single
# invocation cannot distinguish from a correct save/restore.
item 51 00
item 2482
item 51 00
item 2482
item 51 00
item 2482
check "I survives repeated RCLVEL1 (drift check)" [reg I] 5
check "J survives repeated RCLVEL1 (drift check)" [reg J] 6

puts "ij-preservation.t47: all checks passed"
